		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/01/world/30sino-state/30sino-state-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/01/world/30sino-state/30sino-state-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/01/world/30sino-state/30sino-state-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003947073" width="592" height="395" alt="President Xi Jinping of China at the White House state dinner held for him last week. Mr. Xi raised the profile of an adviser, Ding Xuexiang,&lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-president-inner-circle-western-officials.html?ref=world&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt; when he was included in the guest list for the event."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">President Xi Jinping of China at the White House state dinner held for him last week. Mr. Xi raised the profile of an adviser, Ding Xuexiang,<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-president-inner-circle-western-officials.html?ref=world"></a> when he was included in the guest list for the event.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Mike Theiler/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/30/the-gatekeeper-in-xi-jinpings-inner-circle/" data-title="The &#8216;Gatekeeper&#8217; in Xi Jinping&#8217;s Inner Circle" data-description="Ding Xuexiang has emerged as the latest notable entrant into the Chinese president&#039;s core group of advisers. Mr. Ding was serving as the head of the Shanghai party committeeâs General Office in 2007 when Mr. Xi arrived there.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He was on the guest list for the state dinner that President Obama hosted for President Xi Jinping of China on Friday. He was also one of four officials that Mr. Xi took with him to meet Mr. Obama and an American policy delegation in Beijing in November.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-president-inner-circle-western-officials.html?ref=world">Ding Xuexiang</a>, 53, has emerged as the latest notable entrant into <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/26/world/asia/xi-jinping-china-president-inner-circle-western-officials.html?ref=world">Mr. Xiâs inner circle</a>, which has a reputation for being secretive and purposefully distant toward Westerners.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ding serves as a secretary to Mr. Xi, after a career as a Communist Party cadre in Shanghai, where Mr. Xi spent eight months as party chief in 2007 after a political purge there. Mr. Ding moved to Beijing in 2013 after being appointed deputy director of the General Office of the partyâs Central Committee. The director of the General Office is Li Zhanshu, an old friend of Mr. Xiâs from Hebei Province who essentially serves as Mr. Xiâs chiefÂ­ ofÂ­ staff. The General Office has the task of coordinating administrative affairs for senior party officials.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDing Xuexiang is more of the gatekeeper guy,â said <a href="//csis.org/expert/christopher-k-johnson">Christopher K. Johnson</a>, a former China analyst for the C.I.A. who is now at the Center for Strategic and International Studies in Washington. âHeâs smart. Thereâs no doubt Xi listens to his thinking. He will likely become the General Office director once Li Zhanshu goes.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-37723"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ding was the head of the Shanghai party committeeâs General Office in 2007 when Mr. Xi arrived, and he was soon promoted to the post of secretary general of the municipal party committee.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHere is another young man, and he was born after 1960,â Mr. Xi said of Mr. Ding while introducing his municipal cabinet to Chinese reporters that May, according to a 2013 article in Beijing Youth Daily.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The article said that when Mr. Ding was head of the Shanghai partyâs General Office, he wrote an article for Secretary Work magazine that laid out his philosophy for serving as an aide to leaders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe prosperity of a country depends on political affairs, and the achievement of political affairs relies on the work of the assistant,â he wrote. âThe general office of the party committee, as the think tank of the party committee and brain of the leaders, should place as its first priority its service of consultation.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Secretaries must âplan with the heart of a commander despite having a post as a soldier,â he wrote. âIf you cannot do this, it will all be in vain, no matter how much additional effort you make and how much more work you do.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Ding has a technical background typical of many officials of his generation. He graduated from Northeast Heavy Machinery Institute and worked at the Shanghai Research Institute of Materials from 1982 to 1999, before beginning his rapid rise through the party ranks. His first cadre position was as a deputy director on the science and technology work committee of the Shanghai municipal party committee.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Under Mr. Xi, the General Office has been expanding its duties and moving into the realm of policy. Mr. Xi placed the executive office of the secretive <a href="//yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/xi-jinping%25E2%2580%2599s-high-risk-policy-needs-national-security-commission">National Security Commission</a>, which he created to defend the party against <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/30/world/asia/chinese-national-security-law-aims-to-defend-party-grip-on-power.html">domestic and foreign threats</a>, inside the General Office.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe General Office staff has grown dramatically under Xi,â Mr. Johnson said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There are about 300 people from the General Office who âplay an important role in pushing paperwork and decision documents to Xi and act as the staff of the N.S.C.,â David M. Lampton, director of China Studies at the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies, wrote in a paper on the commission this year.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Political observers in Beijing have noted others in Mr. Xi&#8217;s orbit with secretarial roles. One is Zhong Shaojun, who is Mr. Xiâs secretary on the Central Military Commission. In 2013, he was appointed deputy director of the military commissionâs General Office.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Before that, Mr. Zhong had a civilian career as a party cadre. A native of Zhejiang Province, he worked there as a propaganda official when Mr. Xi was the provincial party chief. He was then transferred to Shanghai, where he worked under Mr. Ding in the General Office. His last move was to Beijing. At each step, Mr. Zhong was transferred at the same time that Mr. Xi moved into posts in those cities, indicating that he has been one of Mr. Xiâs most trusted aides, according to one report online.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A state television news clip from 2013 shows Mr. Zhong visiting a satellite launch base in Gansu Province with Mr. Xi and wearing a green, short-sleeve Peopleâs Liberation Army uniform that has shoulder insignia designating him as a colonel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another man, Zhu Guofeng, has also been labeled a secretary to Mr. Xi. In footage from state television he was seen at a meeting with Mr. Xi and other world leaders during the Boao Forum for Asia in southern China in April 2013.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">To understand the potential in a person serving as secretary to a high-ranking figure, one need look no further than Mr. Xi himself. From 1979 to 1982, he served as a secretary, known as mishu in Chinese, to Gen. Geng Biao, then the minister of defense. It was Mr. Xi&#8217;s first job after he completed his formal university education.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Yufan Huang contributed research.</em></p>
<h4>The Inner Circle</h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Based on research and interviews by The New York Times, here are some things to know about five other men who, to varying degrees, act as advisers to Mr. Xi.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Wang Qishan,</strong><em> 67, head of the Communist Partyâs Central Commission for Discipline Inspection, Politburo Standing Committee member</em>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A fan of âHouse of Cards,â he has told people that he pays special attention to the role of party whip, according to a <a href="//news.ifeng.com/shendu/fhzk/detail_2013_12/05/31837407_0.shtml">Hong Kong magazine</a>. That is the job of the devious and menacing Frank Underwood character at the start of the show.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While a former finance official, he met often with Henry M. Paulson Jr., the Goldman Sachs chief executive who later became United States Treasury secretary under President George W. Bush. Mr. Paulson wrote that during the 2008 financial crisis, Mr. Wang said: âWe arenât sure we should be learning from you anymore.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He is married to the daughter of Yao Yilin, a former viceÂ­ premier. He does not have children, which some political insiders say gives him fewer vested interests and makes him more immune to corruption.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Li Zhanshu, </strong><em>65, head of the General Office of the Communist Partyâs Central Committee, Politburo member</em>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He drank socially with Mr. Xi when the two were countyÂ­-level party chiefs in Hebei Province in the 1980s.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He once said in an interview that he abides by a three Â­nos principle: No messing around with other people, no playing games, no loafing on the job.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An uncle, Li Zhengtong, died in 1949 fighting as a Communist soldier against the Kuomintang. That took place less than a month after the uncle had gotten married. Mr. Li has described his father bringing the uncleâs body back to their village on a cart. In <a href="//m.china.com/jsp/wap/endpage.jsp?forumid=1011&amp;threadid=276032417&amp;page=1&amp;full=true">a 2005 essay memorializing his uncle</a>, Mr. Li wrote: âThere is an endless yearning that dwells deep in my heart. No matter how time flies, my thoughts for him linger.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Liu He,</strong> <em>63, head of the Communist Partyâs Central Leading Group for Financial and Economic Affairs, Central Committee member</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fluent in English, he has an M.B.A. from Seton Hall University and a Master of Public Administration from the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He was awarded a top economics prize in China for a paper in 2012 that compared the 2008 global financial crisis with the Great Depression of the 1930s. He concluded with three lessons for China, including, âHave contingency plans for the worstÂ­-case scenarios.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This summer, as foreign analysts were questioning the stability of Chinaâs economy and its stock market, he told a Hong Kong television station, âThereâs no problem; rest assured,â and, âThereâs no problem with the stock market, either.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Wang Huning,</strong><em> 59, head of the Communist Partyâs Central Policy Research Office, Politburo member.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He spent most of his academic career as a professor in the department of international politics at Fudan University in Shanghai and has been a policy adviser to Presidents Jiang Zemin, Hu Jintao and Xi Jinping.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After a six-Â­month visit to the United States in 1988, he wrote a book, âAmerica Opposes America.â His purpose on the visit was to observe up close the âbiggest capitalist country,â he wrote. âPeople wonder how this nation, with a short history of only 200 years, could become the most developed country in the world.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Wei Chengsi, a former Shanghai official, wrote that he once asked Mr. Wang why he did not describe himself, a known proponent of strong centralized leadership, as a subscriber to âneoÂ­authoritarianism.â Mr. Wang replied: âBecause the Communist Party can only publicly accept one doctrine, and thatâs MarxismÂ­-Leninism.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Gen. Liu Yuan,</strong><em> 64, political commissar of the Logistics Department of the Peopleâs Liberation Army, Central Committee member</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He is the son of Liu Shaoqi, the president of China from 1959 to 1968, who was purged by Mao during the Cultural Revolution and died in 1969 after months of being beaten and tortured.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had an early career as a civilian official in Henan Province, rising to the post of vice governor, before being transferred to the Peopleâs Liberation Army with the rank of major general.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The most vocal critic of corruption in the military, he was the first to challenge Gen. Gu Junshan as well as Gen. Xu Caihou, a vice chairman of the Central Military Commission, which oversees the military. Those two generals were later purged by Mr. Xi on corruption charges.</p>
